Project Report
The purpose of the project report is for you to effectively communicate your
research activities. Prior to beginning your draft of this report, you should carefully
read the following article to help guide your writing:
T. Munzner. Process and pitfalls in writing information visualization papers. In A.
Kerren, J. T. Stasko, J.-D. Fekete, and C. North, editors, Information Visualization:
Human-Centered Issues and Perspectives, LNCS 4950, pages 134–153. Springer,
2008.
Your report should be written in the style of a conference paper. You should provide
adequate descriptions of the following:
• problem domain (users’ tasks and goals for visualizing the data)
• relevant literature
• proposed solution
• case study or scenario of use
• discussion on benefits and limitations
Prepare your article based on the ACM formatting guide:
https://www.acm.org/publications/authors/submissions
You will find that the LaTeX template will produce the best results, but it may take
some time to get familiar with how LaTeX works. This is worth your effort. Take
special care in how references are formatted.
In addition to marking for content, deductions will be made based on poor
formatting, structure, style, grammar, spelling, and referencing. Your paper should
be 7-10 pages.
Academic Integrity
While you may talk about the work on your project with your classmates to help
each other understand what is needed, all the work submitted must be your own
group or individual software development and writing. You are welcome to use
whatever third-party visualization frameworks, tools, and extensions you can find.
However, these details must be clearly documented both within the written
submission and your source code.
Please familiarize yourself with the Generative AI Tools policy specified in the
course syllabus.